<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> The habitats and ecology of <i>Artemisia tridentata </i>subspecies vary sufficiently to justify separate vegetation alliances of this widespread species (Young et al. 2007).<i>A. tridentata vaseyana</i> ssp. </i>vaseyana </i>grows in foothills and on mountain slopes in shallow, well drained, rocky soils. Shrubs can live to 50 years of age. Plants produce prolific seed with high germination rates. Seeds disperse within 4 m of the parent plant and seeds on the soil surface or in duff are viable for up to 5 years (Johnson 2000a). <br/>
<br/>
Plants of <i>Artemisia tridentata</i> ssp. <i>vaseyana </i>are found in many vegetation types, and dominate areas with deeper, well developed soils. This commonly includes areas where soil development has been influenced by volcanic tephra (Young et al. 1977, 2007). <br/>
<br/>
Many forests and woodlands, including stands of the <i>Pinus jeffreyi, Pinus ponderosa, </i>and <i>Juniperus occidentalis </i>alliances, contain open to relatively dense understories of <i>Artemisia tridentata</i> ssp. <i>vaseyana</i>. Following recent vegetation sampling in the Modoc Plateau, a new alliance of <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> / Shrub Understory Alliance can have any of these three tree species and describes this vegetation patterning with <i>Artemisia tridentata</i> spp. <i>vaseyana</i> and/or several other shrub species (VegCAMP 2020). <br/>
<br/>
The <i>Artemisia tridentata</i> spp. <i>vaseyana</i> alliance is characterized by having sparse tree cover in the overstory and evenly distributed shrubs (VegCAMP 2020). These stands typically occur as forest openings or vast expanses in desert uplands. Some stands have high shrub cover with little grass; others have a strong, perennial bunchgrass component that may represent moister or less-disturbed shrub steppe expressions of the alliance. These stands also may be the result of livestock overgrazing or increasing summer drought (West 1983b, 1983c). Other stands with only a few scattered shrubs over an herbaceous layer belong to grassland alliances.<br/>
<br/>
We have chosen to include stands dominated by <i>Symphoricarpos rotundifolius</i> as part of this alliance as the two species are often found together in the Modoc Plateau (VegCAMP 2020). We have adopted the NVC name for these stands, however: <i>Symphoricarpos oreophilus</i>, as they occupy a similar ecological niche. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
