<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Artemisia tridentata </i>does not sprout after fire, and seeds from on- and off-site sources may establish new shrubs after burns. Established seedlings take about a decade to dominate the site. Severe fires that burn the banked seeds and mycorrhizal spores are slow to establish new shrubs (Tirmenstein 1999b). 

<i>A. tridentata </i>increases in importance with longer fire intervals. Short fire intervals of 2-5 years eliminate perennial grasses and nonsprouting shrubs; intervals of 10-30 years eliminate short-lived, sprouting shrubs; intervals of 30-70 years maintain perennial bunchgrasses and nonsprouting shrubs (Johnson 2000a).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (10-150 years)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
