    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Ga-d, Gf, Gh-n). Stands are extensive in the section at higher elevations with well-developed soils, similar to those in Oregon (Franklin and Dyrness 1973), and include various grass species and <i>Purshia tridentata</i> (Young et al. 2007). Stands are characteristically on the upper slopes and ridgetops in this section (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ad). One stand sampled near Schwaub Peak</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Db, Dd-e, Dh, Dj, Dl). Stands occur at higher elevations in the Sweetwater and White mountains. Stands are described on slopes and ridges both above and below the <i>Pinus monophylla</i> woodland belt for Whippoorwill Flat RNA (Cheng 2004). Stands have been sampled near Whitmore Hot Springs (Slaton 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Bd). Stands are scattered at higher elevations throughout the subsection, with high concentrations occurring on Shaffer Mountain, and in the Skedaddle and Cottonwood Mountains (Geographical Information Center (in progress)).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea, Ec, Eh-l, En-o, Eq-r, Et-u). Stands are common as openings in conifer forests throughout the section at higher elevations. Exposed ridgetop stands on volcanic soils are described at Mud Lake RNA (Cheng 2004). Meadow-edge stands are common at high elevations in Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) and have similar ecological conditions as stands of <i>Artemisia rothrockii</i> found further south in the section. Stands of various associations have been sampled in the Northern Sierra Nevada (VegCAMP unpublished)</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fa-d, Ff). Stands have been sampled in the Inyos, the Panamint Range near Telescope Peak and in the Last Chance Mountains (Evens et al 2014)</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da, De, Dg-i, Dm). Stands are common as openings in conifer forests throughout the section at higher elevations. Stands were sampled in Lava Beds National Monument (DiPaolo et al 2015)</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Considerable debate exists over whether the present shrub-dominated stands represent a degraded shrub steppe from grazing, fire management, or climatic change. Young et al. (2007) stated that the <i>Artemisia tridentata </i>spp. <i>vaseyana </i>vegetation in the Modoc Plateau transitioned to <i>Juniperus occidentalis </i>or Pine woodlands in vast areas. They also stated that the species is a preferred browse species for mule deer. 

Fires of short return intervals inhibit <i>Artemisia tridentata; </i>excessive grazing may decrease fire return interval because of the loss of perennial bunchgrasses. However, invasion by <i>Bromus tectorum </i>and other nonnative annuals may eliminate shrubs by increasing the spread and frequency of fire. </div>
</div>

    

    

